Monitoring devices are increasingly required by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think of monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can also be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases such as the example of the small Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of matches but will soon be the size of a watch.
The small Anicka case has stirred up a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We strive to tell everyone that this is not about espionage but only about another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracers in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of poor use of such devices, such as placing them in the bag of someone who is not aware, but I have not yet met such cases."
"The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons, add Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in case of an emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear something like that on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something explicitly when they don't want to be under control.'
"Portable phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long wait," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything to ensure that the child has no electronic device to locate it."
"Actually, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," the psychologist said.
She is aware that such devices can help in an attack that is not prepared by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, he claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the case of aggression.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on a regular basis after a specified period".
"In case the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
'The most expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in an extended position without moving," says Cech.
According to him mobile phones called intelligent ones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formed it with a special prologial.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to the one that is worn on the pendant of the size of a box of lights or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Dr. Weil's Pilina, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracer."
"Or he will realize it after some time, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed as a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of GPS position acquisition systems (which is commonly used as self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
