The prosecutors of the Department of Justice lifted the criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, as a result of a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the woman's husband, announced Wednesday the Senator's lawyers.
The decision terminates the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican of Nevada who was considered a potential Republican candidate in the presidential office in 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case did not make the big national titles last year and adversely affect his career.
Mr. Ensign's office stated that he was "very happy" by the decision, the result of a one-year survey.
The honourable senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to keep any charges against him in this case."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Ministry of Justice, according to which there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign would have conspired to breach a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to get a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the honourable senator's case with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
