Ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seemed in contradiction with the so-called lobbying door ban.
According to evidence that has been made public, "there seems to be a prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to rape and a substantial violation of the law of the turning door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients from an investigation by the government.
Although the department's judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethical lawyers said that the department seemed to be dissuade from political prosecutions after a number of high-level reversals by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to abandon prosecutions against former Senator Ted Stevens for lack of prosecution.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Director General of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Senior Counsel of Mr. Ensign, stated in an interview that on Monday he had received a telephone call from a prosecutor in the Department of Justice and followed up on the following day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's lawyer team had cooperated with the prosecutors to try to convince them that the senator, as her office reaffirmed in a statement on Wednesday, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made in the prosecutor's office.
"I am not comfortable with entering into the details of my discussions with the Ministry of Justice, except to say that we think they have made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to abandon an inquiry following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to Hampton violated the federal electoral law.
