Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another customer from Nevada, Allegiant Air, and asked the transport secretary to set a meeting on behalf of the airline after committing Mr. Hampton to lobbying.
When news of the case came to the surface last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign stated two weeks ago that he intended to have a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said that the senator hoped that the Ethics Committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and put an end to his investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
