Can civilization approach the cleavages?
After a campaign marked by invectiveness and negativity, a minimum of civilization broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a pre-cooperative sign of genuine bipartite cooperation towards the front or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not produce any insight into the great issues to be addressed during the session of the "boxy duck".
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties and the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to mark points.
The Commission's public meeting on the President's deficit on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect beyond the ideological gap, but which, however, still divides the members.
It is barely enough to say that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both parties are now in a period of testing and testing each other to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed in the past two years.
Whether tax, spending, health care or rights, both parties remain at miles away.
Yet, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone," said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration, now next to the Ethics and Public Policy Centre.
"It's inevitable after the elections.
Elections give rise to partisan passions and then collapse.
That's good."
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the "boitous duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax reductions will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve a party or the whole, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is likely to be reached on the extension of unemployment benefits, because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers without employment.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is planned on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "boitous duck", with the ratification of the "New START" Pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing problems of the "lame Duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, or is inevitable.
"Once the things that must be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civilization would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between today and 2012 as a pre-play or shadowboxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the Chamber and to the electors present in the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new Health Care Act.
These partisan positions are now already clear in the initial responses to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, reposing the retirement age and reducing expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, they themselves, have imposed the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee, composed of 18 members, to issue their plans as an official recommendation, and they have had a hard time reaching this number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected members; this suggests that there are little or no grounds for compromise on tax matters today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first year will come next in the form of partisan confrontations, as the Republicans contest Obama's budget, taxes and health care; and then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is widely demonstrated that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans always want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Anyone who will be tried in loss will have to change his mind and find compromises.
But it would nevertheless be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, both party activists see 2010 as a simple prelude to a larger election in 2012.
In view of this reality, the civilization exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take a lot more effort on both sides to find a common ground on matters that divide them again.
