The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
People need to go to Visa Applicants' Service Centres prior to their interview with the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedure for the processing of visas at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to appear at the Visa Applicants' Service Centres (ASCs) before their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will receive biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will present some benefits for the applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, there will be no need to make a payment for an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The bidder will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visas will not have to interview the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants to the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bolets/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
