Avengers and speedy spies hackers
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal which only appears as a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (from any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" U.S. revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits have only reported what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's sinister caricural profile was long for cabaret artists scetch material.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the earlier works.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (he doesn't know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who go to occultism believe only in what they already know, and who confirms what they have already learned.
It's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
Same for secret files.
The informer is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the chief of secret services (unless he could be, as I know, editor at Libération), which retains as true what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the Department of State were the same as those that Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the Heads of State can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into centres of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it's only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put US diplomacy under a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the state department.
So the scandal does not put the victims and the "burreaux" in crisis.
But let us come to the deep nature of what happened.
So, in Orwell's time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been fully proven since, having been able to control each movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when one demonstrates, as now happens, that even crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
The power to control every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the avenger of the citizen - may know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to remove all power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this very powerful injury?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on the line any reserved information - that would be published on a side-by-side sign.
But it's just as obvious as with current technologies, it's just enough to expect to be able to maintain confidential telephone reports.
Nothing easier than discovering whether and when a head of state moved by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that for the moment my forecast is based on science fiction and is therefore Romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government officials who discreetly move in diligence to uncontrollable itineraries, only being carriers of messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in key closed drawers: deep down, the Watergate spying attempt has been less successful than WikiLeaks.
I've had the opportunity to write that technology now advances in crabs, i.e. back-to-back.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephones).
The videocassettes (analogues) had allowed film-makers to explore a step-by-step film, going forward and backward and discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (numerics) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while on the plane, and the travels it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the communications policy and techniques go back to the horse cars.
